Standard 4: Demonstrate management of individual and family resources, including food, clothing, shelter, and transportation.
Demonstrate processes used by individuals and families to set standards, make choices, and satisfy needs and wants for nutrition and wellness, clothing, housing, and transportation.
Apply management and planning skills and processes to organize tasks and responsibilities.
Demonstrate skills in seeking consumer information, taking consumer responsibility, and exercising consumer rights.
Evaluate features, prices, and performance of consumer goods in light of personal standards, goals, and resources.
Determine individual and family responsibilities in conserving, reusing, and recycling resources to maintain the environment.
Assess the use of technology and its impact on quality of life and family resources.
Standard 5: Demonstrate management of financial resources to meet the goals of individuals and families across the life span .
Demonstrate strategies for personal and family financial planning which reflect interrelationships among needs, wants, standards, goals, and economic resources.
Determine financial practices that foster economic self-sufficiency for individuals and families.
Apply management principles to decisions about budgeting, banking, and record keeping.
Analyze required and optional payroll deductions, including income and social security taxes, insurance premiums, savings, and investments.
Demonstrate strategies for preparing tax reports.
Explore and evaluate types and sources of credit and their impacts on long-term financial well-being of individuals and families.
Determine the effects of various risk management strategies on long-term financial well-being, including savings, investments, and insurance.
