FOOD INDUSTRY OCCUPATIONS I, II 1.1 1.2 1.3 1.4 1.5 1.6 1.7 1.8 1.9 1.10 1.11 1.12 1.13 1.14 1.15 1.16 1.17 2.1 2.2 2.3 2.4 2.5 2.6 2.7 Standard 1: Employability Skills Reacts to and solves guest problems effectively.
Makes suggestions to solve operational problems (such as choosing between conflicting priorities, managing multiple projects, or helping a coworker solve a problem) effectively.
Monitors and manages own work time to achieve desired performance.
Performs tasks in order of priority.
When unsure of the order of priority, asks an appropriate supervisor or coworker.
Gives customers correct change.
Communicates thoughts, ideas and information well between the front of the house and back of the house to ensure fast and high-quality guest service.
Works to resolve guests' complaints effectively.
Accommodates guests who have special requests or needs.
Lifts and handles utensils, cooking pots, and other hot items to prevent burns and scalds to self and others.
Demonstrates safety by cleaning up spills to prevent trips and falls without being told.
Lifts heavy items safely to prevent back and other injuries.
Holds, uses, and passes knives correctly to prevent injury to self and others.
Cleans and sanitizes foodservice equipment, utensils, dishes, glasses, flatware, cabinets, counters, woodwork, floors, windows, refrigerators, ranges, sinks, garbage disposals, and trash areas using correct sanitation procedures.
Stores, cooks, and holds different types of food using correct food safety procedures.
Demonstrates steps for avoiding contamination and cross-contamination of foods, including frequent and thorough hand washing.
Demonstrates proper procedures for operating machines and computers.
Locates, understands, and interprets written information in manuals and schedules.
Standard 2: Personal Skills and Characteristics Speaks clearly and courteously to customers, coworkers, supervisors, and professionals.
Actively listens to customers, coworkers, supervisors, and professionals without interrupting.
Asks for supervisory approval when appropriate.
Makes work-related decisions using sound judgment.
Arrives at work on time, or calls in advance with an acceptable reason for being late.
Does not miss scheduled work without calling in advance with an acceptable reason.
Communicates responsibly thoughts, feelings, and ideas regarding work policies and procedures with supervisor.
